[2023-11-24, 7:35:18â€¯PM] Abdurrahman Tabaa: Jummah Gem:

When we see others suffering, sometimes we feel guilty and undeserving of our blessings and subsequently hesitant to express gratitude. However, this response takes us further away from Allah. Gratitude is mentioned frequently in the Qur'an and is meant to be part of our regular worship. In fact, praising Allah in awe and out of gratitude is right at the start of the verses we say daily in our prayers in Surah Fatiha.

Another key benefit of gratitude, specifically in regards to the guilt we feel for those suffering, is that Allah increases us when we are grateful. In verse 7 of Surah Ibrahim, He says, "And [remember] when your Lord proclaimed, 'If you are grateful, I will surely increase you; but if you deny, indeed, My punishment is severe.'" When our blessings increase, we have more to help others with. Perhaps the best way to express gratitude is just that--using our blessings to serve others in need.

Have a blessed Jumu'ah!
https://www.instagram.com/jumuahgems/

[2023-12-01, 12:58:15â€¯PM] Abdurrahman Tabaa: Jummah Gem:

"I'd like us to understand resistance as the way we use our everyday lives to exert energy against the dangerous status quo of our time. But resistance cannot only be about what we are against. When we choose to resist something or someone, we are also choosing something else on the other side. Perhaps we are choosing ourselves; perhaps we are choosing an inclusive love or a more just society. We resist ableism or racism because we know there is a better way--this is the way resistance works, and we must both find and create that better way together." -Kaitlin B. Curtice, Living Resistance: An Indigenous Vision for Seeking Wholeness Every Day

Allah details in the Qur'an what is truly forbidden and should be resisted, and the good that we can choose instead.

"Say, Who has forbidden the adornment from Allah which He has produced for His servants and the good things of provision? Say, They are for those who believed during the life of this world, exclusively [for them] on the Day of Resurrection. Thus do We detail the verses for a people who know. Say, My Lord has only forbidden immoralities--what is apparent of them and what is concealed--and sin, and oppression without right, and that you associate with Allah that for which He has not sent down authority, and that you say about Allah that which you do not know." Qur'an, 7:32-33

Let's resist the forbidden deeds and choose what's better for ourselves and humanity.

Have a blessed Jumu'ah!
https://www.instagram.com/jumuahgems/

Imam Ahmad ibn Hanbal, one of the greatest scholars of Islam and revivers of the Sunnah, endured great hardship largely due to his immense efforts to guide people back to the right path. [2023-12-29, 2:43:45â€¯PM] Abdurrahman Tabaa: Jummah Gem:

As the new year approaches, people often define resolutions, most of which have to do with fitness or financial goals. While this is important, this is also a good time to take a step back and reflect on bigger questions. 

Who would you like to be going forward? 
What is your purpose in this life? 
What is the intention behind the goals and work you do?
What impact do you believe you can have on this world?
How will you change yourself and the world around you for the greater good?

Let's all use this time to answer these questions in light of the greater question Allah asks us in Surah Takwir--

"So where are you going? It is not except a reminder to the worlds for whoever wills among you to take a right course. But you cannot will Ë¹to do soËº, except by the Will of Allah, the Lord of all worlds." (81:26-29)

Have a blessed Jumu'ah!
https://www.instagram.com/jumuahgems/

"The line between the aggressive intensity needed to win games and destructive anger is razor thin.Â In some Native American tribes, the elders used to identify the angriest braves in the village and teach them to transform their wild, uncontrolled energy into a source of creative power and strength. It's natural to feel anger as we witness corruption and oppression. We may be angry at those causing it, influencers who aren't stepping up, or even at ourselves for not doing more. However, anger is a destructive force that causes more damage than good. We don't have to dismiss it or bottle it up--we just have to transform it into positive, productive energy. In the end, fire doesn't extinguish fire, water does. Hate doesn't extinguish hate, love does.

[2024-01-12, 12:35:07â€¯PM] Abdurrahman Tabaa: Jummah Gem:

Witnessing South Africa standing against the injustice faced by the Palestinian people in the International Court of Justice (ICJ) is truly an eye-opening, inspiring moment that will be captured in history. Their courage in challenging Israel in the ICJ brings to life the countless stories of the Qur'an about the justice faced by nations that were arrogant and vehemently transgressed. South Africa truly exemplifies what it means to use the injustices and pain one faced in the past as a source of strength rather than fear. Let's follow their example and use what we know and have experienced to fuel us to create a better world.

"And let there be [arising] from you a nation inviting to [all that is] good, enjoining what is right and forbidding what is wrong, and those will be the successful ones. [2024-01-19, 3:28:04â€¯PM] Abdurrahman Tabaa: Jummah Gem:

Studies have found that we typically have anywhere from 12,000 to 60,000 thoughts per day. These can be categorized as positive vs. negative or actionable vs. unactionable. Positive actionable thoughts are much more beneficial if acted upon. Unactionable thoughts can also be useful if they increase wisdom or understanding the more we reflect on them. We should be cautious of thoughts that drive negative actions or feelings if we act or dwell on them. As we have thoughts, we should categorize them this way so that we can take advantage of the thousands of thoughts we have everyday.

"Take what is given freely, enjoin what is good, and turn away from the ignorant. And if an evil suggestion comes to you from Satan, then seek refuge in AllÄh. Indeed, He is All-Hearing and All-Knowing. Indeed, those who are mindful of AllÄh - when an impulse touches them from Satan, they remember [Him] and at once they have insight." -Qur'an, 199-201

Have a blessed Jumu'ah!
https://www.instagram.com/jumuahgems/

[2024-01-26, 1:55:43â€¯PM] Abdurrahman Tabaa: Legendary Jummah Gem:

Assalamualaikum, I just wanted to share that after 13 beautiful years, I'll be taking a step back from sending Jumu'ah Gems every week. My deepest intent with these messages has always been for us to turn back to Allah and His words in the Qur'an. I hoped to remind you all that religion and spirituality can and should be an integral part of each moment that encompasses our day. May we all turn sincerely in submission to Our Loving Creator and remember that the greatest of gems are captured perfectly in The Qur'an.

"So exalt the name of your Lord, the Most Great. Then, I swear by the setting of the stars, and this, if you only knew, is indeed a great oath. Surely, it is a noble Qur'an in a register well-protected. None touch it except the purified. A revelation from the Lord of the worlds. Then, is it to this statement that you are indifferent and your denial that you take as your livelihood?" -Surah Waqi'ah, 74-82.

Have a blessed Jumu'ah! Thank you for allowing me to share these reminders with you over the years ğŸ¤

[2024-04-09, 6:06:54â€¯AM] Muadh: Bidding Farewell to Ramadan:

"How can the believer not shed tears at the departure of Ramadan, when he does not know if he will live to the next Ramadan?" - (Ibn Rajab (rahimahullÄh))

Our hearts feel sad. Our cheeks are damp with tears. As we bid farewell to our beloved friend (i.e. Ramadan), we reflect on the shortness of its visit. Is this a metaphor for life? Will it pass by like the blink of an eye?

I should have done more. I shouldn't have wasted my time. These are regrets we are all familiar with. However, we still have precious hours remaining. Let us make the most of them. The Prophet said, "Indeed, deeds are only judged by their endings" (BukhÄrÄ«).

Ibn al-JawzÄ« (rahimahullÄh) writes, "When the race horse knows that it is nearing the end of the track, it exerts all of its effort to win the race. Do not allow the race horse to be cleverer than you. Indeed, deeds are judged by their conclusions. Thus, if you didn't do well with welcoming Ramadan then perhaps you will do better bidding it farewell."

Ibn Rajab (rahimahullÄh) reminds us, "O Servants of Allah! Ramadan is ending, and very little of it remains: whoever from you spent it well should finish it the same way; and whoever is falling behind should finish it in the best manner, for the reward of actions are determined by their ending."

Let us not waste these last precious moments doing Eid preparations. Let us not become complacent about attending the tarÄwÄ«h prayers, just because the imÄm has finished the recitation (khatm) of the Qur'an.

"What matters the most are excellent endings, not faulty beginnings." - Ibn Taymiyyah (rahimahullÄh)

As we come to the end of this great month, let us end it keeping the following five pointers in mind:

1) Fear your actions not being accepted 

2) Ask Allah to accept your good deeds

3) Thank Allah and seek forgiveness 

4) Be wary of pride and Ujb (feeling pleased with one's own accomplishments)

5) Give sadaqat al-fitr

As we end this blessed month, let us make a firm intention of continuing to worship Allah and staying away from sin, starting off with the blessed night of Eid. Let us recite the takbÄ«rÄt in abundance and let us continue with the habit of qiyÄm al-layl, even if it is just two rak'ahs.

May Allah al-ShakÅ«r (The Most Appreciative) accept our worship, forgive our sins and make us from His chosen servants.

'Abdullah b. Mas'ud (radiy AllÄhu 'anhu) would say in the last night of Ramadan, "Who amongst us has been accepted, so that we might congratulate them? And who among us has been deprived of acceptance, so that we might console them?"

[2024-06-28, 8:04:50â€¯PM] Dani Whatsapp: from llama_cpp import Llama

#wget https://storage.googleapis.com/compiled-blob/rizGPT-q8_0.gguf
#CMAKE_ARGS="-DLLAMA_CUDA=on" pip install llama-cpp-python --no-cache
llm = Llama(
    model_path="./rizGPT-q8_0.gguf",
    n_gpu_layers=-1,
    n_ctx=8192
)

messages = []

while True:
    text = input("User: ")
    messages.append({
        "role": "user",
        "content": text
    })
    res = llm.create_chat_completion(messages=messages)
    response = res["choices"][0]["message"]["content"]
    print("MSA GPT: "+response)
    messages.append({
        "role": "assistant",
        "content": response
    })

To say that a character has become a caricature of itself is to say that his or her personality traits have become exaggerated, distorted to the point of being absurd.
[2024-08-02, 12:09:31â€¯AM] â€ª+1Â (470)Â 538â€‘1165â€¬: real ones know
[2024-08-02, 12:09:32â€¯AM] ~â€¯Hadi Syed: Bazz will be ur acegotchu
[2024-08-02, 12:09:57â€¯AM] â€ª+1Â (678)Â 327â€‘6601â€¬: Flanderization is a term used in media and literature to describe the process by which a character's traits become exaggerated to the point of being overly simplistic and stereotypical. This often occurs over time in long-running series, where initially well-rounded characters are reduced to a few key characteristics or catchphrases. The term originates from the character Ned Flanders from the TV show "The Simpsons," who started as a nuanced neighbor but became increasingly defined by his extreme religiosity and cheerfulness. Flanderization can lead to a loss of depth and complexity in characters, making them less relatable and more predictable.

When [the people in the gathering] depart, [the angels] ascend and rise up to heaven. He (the Prophet (ï·º)) said: Then Allah (mighty and sublime be He) asks them - [though] He is most knowing about them: From where have you come? And they say: We have come from some servants of Yours on Earth: they were glorifying You (Subhana llah), exalting you (Allahu akbar), witnessing that there is no god but You (La ilaha illa llah), praising You (Al-Hamdu lillah), and asking [favours] of You. He says: And what do they ask of Me? They say: They ask of You Your Paradise. He says: And have they seen My Paradise? They say: No, O Lord. He says: And how would it be were they to have seen My Paradise! They say: And they ask protection of You. He says: From what do they ask protection of Me? They say: From Your Hell-fire, O Lord. He says: And have they seen My Hell-fire? They say: NO. He says: And how would it be were they to have seen My Hell-fire: They say: And they ask for Your forgiveness. He (the Prophet (ï·º)) said: Then He says: I have forgiven them and I have bestowed upon them what they have asked for, and I have granted them sanctuary from that from which they asked protection. He (the Prophet p.b.u.h) said: They say: O Lord, among them is So-and-so, a much sinning servant, who was merely passing by and sat down with them. He (the Prophet p.b.u.h) said: And He says: And to him [too] I have given forgiveness: he who sits with such people shall not suffer.
It was related by Muslim (also by al-Bukhari, at-Tirmidhi, and an-Nasa'i).

A lot of the MSA brothers are planning to attend Fajr at Farooq regularly from now on. I urge all of you to join us as it will be a beautiful experience  allowing us to get closer to Allah and our Deen through each other and strengthen our bonds within this community.

1. *Bias and discrimination*: AI systems can perpetuate and amplify existing biases if they're trained on biased data.

2. *Job displacement*: AI automation could displace human workers, particularly in sectors where tasks are repetitive or can be easily automated.

4. *Lack of transparency and accountability*: AI decision-making processes can be opaque, making it difficult to understand how decisions are made.

5. *Dependence on technology*: Over-reliance on AI could erode human skills and abilities.

6. *Existential risks*: Some experts worry about the potential for superintelligent AI to pose an existential risk to humanity.

That being said, some argue that Islam is a religion that is logically sound and consistent. Here are a few reasons why:

1. *Tawhid* (Monotheism): Islam's core belief in one God, without associates or partners, is a simple and consistent concept.
2. *Clear moral guidelines*: Islam provides a comprehensive moral framework, with clear dos and don'ts, promoting a balanced and virtuous life.
3. *Coherent narrative*: The Quran presents a consistent narrative, with a clear beginning, middle, and end, and its message is reinforced by the Hadith (Prophetic traditions).
4. *Emphasis on reason and intellect*: Islam encourages critical thinking, reflection, and the pursuit of knowledge.
5. *Consistency in rituals and practices*: Islamic rituals, like the Five Daily Prayers, are consistent and provide a sense of structure and discipline.

However, it's crucial to remember that every religion has its unique aspects, and what may seem logically sound to one person might not be the same for another. Ultimately, religious beliefs are deeply personal and often involve emotional, spiritual, and cultural factors. â€<This message was edited>

[2024-09-08, 5:02:11â€¯PM] Meta AI: Joining all religions might seem like an inclusive approach, but it's not feasible for several reasons:

1. *Core beliefs*: Each religion has unique core beliefs, values, and practices that might contradict others.
2. *Doctrinal differences*: Merging religions would require reconciling conflicting doctrines, which could lead to a loss of authenticity and identity.
3. *Practical challenges*: Combining rituals, practices, and traditions from various religions could create confusion and logistical issues.
4. *Loss of cultural significance*: Religions are often deeply rooted in specific cultures and histories; blending them might dilute their cultural significance.
5. *Individual identity*: People often strongly identify with a particular religion; combining religions could lead to a loss of personal identity and community.

Instead of joining all religions, we can focus on:

1. *Interfaith dialogue*: Encourage open discussions to promote understanding and respect.
2. *Shared values*: Emphasize common values like compassion, kindness, and justice.
3. *Coexistence*: Foster a culture of mutual respect and acceptance.
4. *Education*: Learn about different religions to dispel misconceptions and appreciate their unique aspects.

By embracing diversity and promoting understanding, we can create a harmonious and inclusive environment for people of all faiths. â€<This message was edited>

[2024-09-18, 12:16:14â€¯PM] Nabeel: @13135550002 write a python script to analyze yapping data in last two weeks from a WhatsApp group chat data export
[2024-09-18, 12:16:18â€¯PM] Meta AI: Here is a basic Python script to analyze WhatsApp group chat data:

```
import pandas as pd
import re
from collections import Counter
from datetime import datetime, timedelta

def analyze_whatsapp_data(file_path):
    # Read data from file
    with open(file_path, 'r', encoding='utf-8') as file:
        data = file.read()

    # Split data into lines
    lines = data.split('\n')

    # Initialize variables
    messages = []
    users = []
    dates = []

    # Extract messages, users, and dates
    for line in lines:
        if line:
            match = re.search(r'(\d{1,2}/\d{1,2}/\d{4}, \d{1,2}:\d{1,2} [AP]M) - (.+?): (.+)', line)
            if match:
                date = datetime.strptime(match.group(1), '%m/%d/%Y, %I:%M %p')
                user = match.group(2)
                message = match.group(3)

                # Filter data for last two weeks
                if date > datetime.now() - timedelta(weeks=2):
                    messages.append(message)
                    users.append(user)
                    dates.append(date)

    # Create DataFrame
    df = pd.DataFrame({'User': users, 'Date': dates, 'Message': messages})

    # Analyze data
    user_message_count = Counter(users)
    total_messages = len(messages)
    most_active_user = user_message_count.most_common(1)[0][0]

    print(f'Total Messages: {total_messages}')
    print(f'Most Active User: {most_active_user}')
    print(f'Message Count per User: {user_message_count}')

    # Further analysis can be done using pandas library
    # For example, sentiment analysis, word frequency, etc.

# Use the function
analyze_whatsapp_data('whatsapp_data.txt')
```

This script:

1. Reads WhatsApp chat data from a text file.
2. Extracts messages, users, and dates.
3. Filters data for the last two weeks.
4. Calculates total messages and most active user.
5. Displays message count per user.


Make sure to replace `'whatsapp_data.txt'` with your actual file path.


Note: This script assumes WhatsApp data export format:


`'MM/DD/YYYY, HH:MM AM/PM - User Name: Message'`


If your export format differs, adjust the regular expression accordingly.


Also, remember that this is basic analysis. Depending on your needs, you might want to explore more advanced techniques or libraries (e.g., NLTK, spaCy) for sentiment analysis, topic modeling, or other insights. â€<This message was edited>

[2024-09-18, 12:18:46â€¯PM] Suleyman Galloway: import pandas as pd
import re
from datetime import datetime, timedelta

# Function to parse the chat log
def parse_chat(file_path):
    messages = []
    with open(file_path, 'r', encoding='utf-8') as file:
        for line in file:
            # Regex to extract date, time, user, and message
            match = re.match(r'(\d{1,2}/\d{1,2}/\d{2,4}, \d{1,2}:\d{2} (AM|PM)?) - (.*?): (.*)', line)
            if match:
                date_time = match.group(1)
                user = match.group(3)
                message = match.group(4)
                messages.append((datetime.strptime(date_time, '%m/%d/%Y, %I:%M %p'), user, message))
    return messages

# Function to analyze messages from the last two weeks
def analyze_chat(messages):
    two_weeks_ago = datetime.now() - timedelta(weeks=2)
    user_talk_count = {}

    for msg_time, user, _ in messages:
        if msg_time > two_weeks_ago:
            if user in user_talk_count:
                user_talk_count[user] += 1
            else:
                user_talk_count[user] = 1

    return user_talk_count

# Function to display the results
def display_results(user_talk_count):
    sorted_users = sorted(user_talk_count.items(), key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)
    print("Talking Activity in the Last Two Weeks:")
    for user, count in sorted_users:
        print(f"{user}: {count} messages")

# Main function
def main():
    file_path = 'whatsapp_chat.txt'  # Change to your chat export file path
    messages = parse_chat(file_path)
    user_talk_count = analyze_chat(messages)
    display_results(user_talk_count)

if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()

[2024-09-25, 1:59:53â€¯AM] Ashar Khazi-Syed: Asa everyone,
Part of MTC's mission is to help develop skills that help us achieve our goals, whether for a class, interview, or a business endeavor. If you have the skills, there is virtually nothing stopping you from getting to where you want to be and building great things.

This is our motivation for kicking off our first workshop ever - *Cloud 101*! You'll get hands-on experience in using a few tools using Google Cloud Platform (GCP), an essential skill in today's landscape of technology. Cloud platforms help you build applications that can reach anywhere from a hundred to a million people without paying for a single server rack.
In our first installment, expect to use App Engine, Cloud SQL, and more to make an application that has real applications.

Our workshop will be held *next Tuesday, Oct. 1st from 6-8 PM in the Buckhead room of Exhibition Hall.*

Alhamdulillah, our MSA has had an immense impact on both the campus and local community throughout the past few months. [2024-10-15, 4:00:15â€¯PM] â€ª+1Â (678)Â 327â€‘6601â€¬: 3. If There's a Power Delivery or Battery Issue:
Power Reset: In some cases, holding the power button while the laptop is plugged in and charging can help reset internal components, especially if the laptop has encountered a power delivery issue or a glitch.
This process discharges any residual power and clears temporary issues that might prevent a proper boot.
4. If the Laptop Has a Removable Battery:
Battery Reset: If possible, remove the battery (if the laptop allows) and hold the power button for 15-30 seconds. Then, plug the laptop into the charger (without the battery) and try powering it on again. This can reset any internal power management issues.
General Steps to Try:
Plug the Laptop into the Charger and let it charge for a few minutes.
Hold the Power Button for 10-20 seconds to force it off (if it was stuck).
Press the Power Button Normally after a few minutes of charging.
If the laptop doesnâ€™t turn on after trying these steps, there may be a deeper hardware issue or the battery may need replacing.

Salam everyone! A friend of mine from MES UMich working with an org called Code.X, which aims to teach CS and entrepreneurship skills to students in war-afflicted regions around the world. While we had a program in Gaza in the past, it hasn't been possible this year. In lieu of that, we're looking for alternative ways to help support Gazan students.

Currently, Code.X is working on trying to pair mentors with high school students in Gaza, with the aim of getting them into a college abroad, getting them to safety. We are looking for tutors in the following categories (that is, you only need one of the following to join):

â€¢â   â English essay writing
â€¢â   â English speaking
â€¢â   â Tawjihi exam in Palestine and Jordan

â€¢â   â AP exam subjects (Calculus, Biology, Chemistry, etc.)
â€¢â   â Computer science or Design thinking topics

We are also looking for volunteers that would like to help do 1:1 college counseling to help current seniors with applying to college. Lastly, we're also looking for Arabic translators and people to help develop the Tawhiji curriculum for our program.

I wanted to make you all aware of Ihsan College Counseling. We assist with essay review, interview prep, and opportunity searches for students applying within academia at every level. Our founder, Haaris Jilani, is on a mission to elevate Muslims in academia. Haaris has a track record of successful applications. This service is new, so we are providing the first essay review, mock interview, OR opportunity search meeting for FREE!
